      <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
	<p>This edition is based on <ref target="bibl:CTI">Burgess and Indraji 1881</ref>. The phrase <foreign xml:lang="mi-Latn">selarūpakama</foreign> refers to the pairs of figures in the back corners of the cave.</p>
      </div>
      <div type="edition" xml:lang="mi-Latn">
	<p>
	  <lb n="1"/>
	    mahā<choice><sic>bhojiya</sic><corr>bhojīya</corr></choice> sāḍageriya
	    <persName key="pers:Ku-Vijayā">vijayāya</persName>
	  <lb n="2"/>
	    mahābhojasa maṃdavasa
	    <persName key="pers:Ku-Skandapālita">khaṃdapālitasa</persName>
	    upajīvīnaṃ
	  <lb n="3"/>
	    <persName key="pers:Ku-Sulasadatta">sulasadatasa</persName>
	    <persName key="pers:Ku-Uttaradattā">utaradatāya</persName>
	    ca putānaṃ bhātūnaṃ lekha
	  <lb n="4"/>
	    kā <persName key="pers:Ku-Śivabhūti">sivabhūtimhā</persName>
	    kaneṭhasa <persName key="pers:Ku-Śivama">sivamasa</persName>
	    deyadhaṃaṃ lenaṃ
	  <lb n="5"/>
	    saha <choice><sic>bhayāya</sic><corr>bhāyāya</corr></choice>
	    <persName key="pers:Ku-Vijayā-2">vijayāya</persName> putānaṃ ca sa
	    <persName key="pers:Ku-Sulasadatta-2">sulasadatasa</persName>
	    <persName key="pers:Ku-Śivapālita">siva<lb n="6" break="no"/>pālitasa</persName>
	    <persName key="pers:Ku-Sarpila">sapilasa</persName>
	    ca selarūpakamaṃ duhutūnaṃ
	  <lb n="7"/>
	    sa <persName key="pers:Ku-Sarpā">sapāya</persName>
	    <persName key="pers:Ku-Śivapālitā">sivapālitāya</persName>
	    <persName key="pers:Ku-Śivadattā">sivadatāya</persName>
	    <persName key="pers:Ku-Sulasadattā">sulasadatāya</persName> sa thaṃbhā  
	</p>
      </div>
      <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
	<p>
	  This is the meritorious gift of a leṇa by
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Śivama">Śivama</persName>, the youngest after
	  the writer <persName key="pers:Ku-Śivabhūti">Śivabhūti</persName>,
	  among the sons of
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Sulasadatta">Sulasadatta</persName> and
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Uttaradattā">Uttaradattā</persName> (who are
	  full) brothers and servants of the Mahābhoja Mandava
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Skandapālita">Skandapālita</persName>, the son of Mahābhojī Sāḍagerī
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Vijayā">Vijayā</persName>,—with the rock
	  carving by his (Śivama’s) wife
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Vijayā-2">Vijayā</persName> and his sons
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Sulasadatta2">Sulasadatta</persName>,
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Śivapālita">Śivapālita</persName>,
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Śivadatta">Śivadatta</persName>, and
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Sarpila">Sarpila</persName>; and the pillars
	  by his daughters
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Sarpā">Sarpā</persName>,
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Śivapālitā">Śivapālitā</persName>,
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Śivadattā">Śivadattā</persName>, and
	  <persName key="pers:Ku-Sulasadattā">Sulasadattā</persName>.
	</p>
      </div>
